{{dablink|This article refers to the businessman from Quebec. For his father, see [[George Benson Hall]]}} {{Infobox person | name = George Benson Hall Jr. | birth_date = {{Birth year|1810}} | birth_place = [[Amherstburg, Ontario|Amherstburg]], [[Upper Canada]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1876|09|04|1810}} | death_place = [[Montmorency, Quebec|Montmorency]], [[Quebec]] | spouse = Mary Jane Patterson }} '''George Benson Hall Jr.''' (1810 &ndash; September 4, 1876) was a businessman involved in the [[Quebec]] lumber business. On his death, the Quebec ''Morning Chronicle'' described him as "one of Quebec’s most prominent and enterprising citizens".
He was born in [[Amherstburg, Ontario|Amherstburg]], [[Upper Canada]], the son of [[George Benson Hall]] and Angelica Fortier. In 1843, he married Mary Jane Patterson, the daughter of [[Peter Patterson (businessman)|Peter Patterson]]. On the death of his father-in-law, he became [[seigneurial system of New France|seigneur]] for Beauport, the last person to hold that title.<ref name="toponym">[http://www4.ville.quebec.qc.ca/toponymie_repertoire/rues/benson_hall.shtml Répertoire des toponymes, Ville de Québec] (French)</ref> Hall established a milling complex at the [[Montmorency Falls]] in 1851, which eventually grew to employ members of 800 families at [[Beauport, Quebec|Beauport]]. He served as an alderman for [[Quebec City]] from 1853 to 1862. Hall died at Montmorency, at the time one of the richest lumber operators in Canada. He was also known for his generosity to the under-privileged of his community.<ref name="toponym"/>
In ''The storied province of Quebec'', the Hall [[sawmill]]s at Montmorency are described as "the greatest in the world".<ref>{{cite web | last = Wood | first = WCH | title = The storied province of Quebec | page = 402 | publisher = | location = | year = 1931 | url = http://www.ourroots.ca/e/toc.aspx?id=8820 | accessdate = 2008-12-04}}</ref>
